but insisting he distinctly remembered having no conversation in 
the 1980s with a pennsylvania democrat quoted as saying quayle 
told him he rode out vietnam in the guard 
bush calling the controversy a tempest in a teapot and 
asserting that his initial campaign swing has gone great except 
for this frenzy of media interest in quayles military record 
whether that assessment is accurate remains to be seen 
quayle seems likely to continue to have to fight portrayals of 
himself as a wealthy young man who spoke in favor of the vietnam 
war but had strings pulled to avoid the draft as his college 
student deferment was about to expire 
bush a navy bomber pilot who saw extensive combat in world war 
ii defended his running mate saying that the vietnam war years in 
which quayle now 41 pondered his own military service were 
different times 
as for quayle being vulnerable in the area of defense an area 
in which bush has portrayed michael dukakis as weak the vice 
president said the difference between the person im running 
against and my running mate are night and day on defense 
bush aides insist they are happy with how quayle has handled 
himself in publicly answering questions about his military record 
quayle himself says he does not feel the issue has overshadowed 
bush 
but there was a clear change in campaign strategy after quayles 
outdoor news conference friday that was piped over a public address 
system to quayles hometown supporters their booing of reporters 
questions and cheering of quayles answers helped create a 
circuslike atmosphere reminiscent of a roman gladiatorial bout 
while bush remained out of sight in a holding room 
that day on which the ticket opened its first joint campaign 
trip in the nations heartland quayle dominated news stories about 
the event 
the next day bush took charge defending his running mate in no 
uncertain terms at a joint news conference and declaring that 
quayles qualifications and background had been examined to his 
satisfaction 
bush said his aides had to spend a lot of time last week running 
down rumor after insidious rumor and added that the 
controversy is behind us 
however some questions may yet need to be answered 
there have been conflicting reports for example on whether 
there were vacancies in the guard at the time quayle entered or 
whether there was a waiting list quayle has said he cannot recall 
those kinds of details 
and he has not spelled out publicly the extent of his knowledge 
about what calls were made on his behalf or to whom they were made 
a retired guard official who is a friend of quayles family and 
worked for the family newspaper has said he did contact the guard 
on quayles behalf the commander of the guard unit to which quayle 
was assigned however has said he did not receive a call from 
anyone urging quayles enlistment 
quayle insists that no rules were broken in the way he 
entered the guard he says he was willing to serve in vietnam had 
his unit been called up although he concedes that he was generally 
aware the likelihood of that happening was not great 
quayle has been angered at implications that he was trying to 
avoid the draft although he has tried to appear unperturbed 
throughout the controversy over the weekend quayle appeared not 
to hear some spectators chants of quayle who went in your 
place or to see signs reading this quayle is a chicken 
he seems to be philosophical about the most intense and public 
scrutiny of his meteoric political career 
im in politics in what they call the big leagues quayle 
says adding running for the vice presidency is a definite 
honor 
</TEXT>
