<TEXT>
foreign policy is getting very little 
attention from the candidates as the campaign gets started the 
republicans seem to be content to play vaguely on george bushs 
experience while the democrats are saying even less 
even so the basic approach of the two parties is becoming 
clear bush and his running mate sen daniel quayle intend to 
sound the traditional conservative themes of a powerful military 
structure and keeping a wary eye on the russians 
dukakis and his running mate sen lloyd bentsen are playing 
down ideology and playing up competence being careful to 
strike a skeptical stance on the soviets while sounding the peace 
theme 
both sides are bound to get more specific in the 2 months of 
campaigning ahead its likely to get sticky bush will be 
challenged about the reagan administrations secret arms sale to 
iran while dukakis lack of foreign policy experience will be 
tested over a wide range of issues 
dont look for foreign policy treatises though campaigning for 
president in the television age encourages snappy or catchy 
oneliners not a thoughtful exposition of how the candidates stand 
on tricky arms control issues the arabisrael dispute leftist 
movements in central america and apartheid in south africa 
besides politicians and their managers operate on the theory 
the voters are far more concerned with pocketbook issues such as 
jobs and inflation than with american foreign policy 
there have been striking exceptions and mixed results franklin 
d roosevelt ran for a fourth term as president in 1944 while the 
united states was still at war the overriding issue was whether to 
take a chance on changing leaders the voters stuck with roosevelt 
in 1972 on the other hand george mcgovern the democratic 
candidate ran primarily as an antiwar candidate whose opposition 
to american involvement in vietnam and cambodia was the central 
theme of his futile race against president richard nixon 
the 1988 campaign is just now unfolding but there is no reason 
to believe either the republicans or democrats will give that sort 
of weight to a single foreign policy issue 
in fact the selections of quayle and bentsen suggest the 
presidential candidates intend to place the focus elsewhere 
bushs choice of quayle is above all a gesture to the gops most 
conservative elements while dukakis chose bentsen primarily for 
his experience in congress and his ties to conservative democrats 
especially in texas 
in 1960 when nixon was pondering a running mate for his first 
race for the presidency he assembled 36 party elders at a midnight 
meeting in chicago the governor of illinois william stratton 
offered this advice you can say all you want about foreign 
affairs but what is really important is the price of hogs in 
chicago 
nixon picked henry cabot lodge who had served as the us 
permanent representative at the united nations they lost to john 
kennedy and lyndon johnson but nixons explanation as recalled by 
former undersecretary of state warren christopher may still be 
relevant if you ever let the democrats campaign only on domestic 
issues they will beat us our only hope is to keep it on foreign 
policy 
that doesnt mean however that the candidate has to be an 
expert on the pecking order in the kremlin the history of the west 
bank or the strengths and weaknesses of the nicaraguan economy 
ronald reagan won in 1980 without any experience in foreign 
affairs he lacked the background to be specific about foreign 
policy issues but he had a welldeveloped image of opposing 
communism and he relied on generalities whenever dealing with the 
soviets the primary foreign policy issue of our time came to 
the fore 
reagan is leaving office on an entirely different note 
he has held four summit meetings with soviet leader mikhail s 
gorbachev and signed a treaty with moscow to scrap 
intermediaterange nuclear missiles 
bush his vice president is trying to capitalize on the 
improvement in ussoviet relations suggesting he is far more 
capable than dukakis to maintain the momentum 
the fact that reagan like dukakis was inexperienced when he 
ran for the presidency is not stopping bush from questioning the 
credentials of his opponent 
</TEXT>
