<TEXT>
a new edition of upton sinclairs the 
jungle an expose of squalid conditions in the chicago 
stockyards will restore whole chapters cut to make the book more 
marketable a book historian says 
sinclair cut his original manuscript by a third for the 1906 
doubleday page edition which caused meat sales to slump and 
spurred president theodore roosevelt to order an investigation that 
led to the nations first pure food and drug act 
gene degruson a professor and curator of rare books at 
pittsburg kan state university was quoted in todays new york 
times as saying that considering the material that was expunged 
from the original its amazing that the published book had any 
impact whatsoever 
despite his protestations that he wished the novel published 
as he had written it revision was drastic degruson wrote in the 
introduction to the new edition due in october from st lukes 
press of memphis tenn 
most of the deletions pertained to socialism but paragraphs 
criticizing the press and derogatory comments about big 
business selfmade men captains of industry and marriage also 
were deleted 
degruson said he pieced together the original novel from a 
truckload of rotting paper given to him in 1980 by a young man who 
had been hired to clean out the cellar of a nearby farm the 
original novel had been serialized in a weekly newspaper the 
appeal but the special edition that contained the final eight 
chapters and the conclusion had been lost until degruson found it 
among the papers from the farm 
sinclair died in a bound brook nj nursing home in 1968 at 
the age of 90 one year after he returned to the white house to 
watch president johnson sign the wholesome meat act an expansion 
of the bill his book inspired 
