<TEXT>
the government on monday 
withdrew a widely criticized bill that would force the evictions of 
tens of thousands of blacks living in areas designated for whites 
critics said the bill which would require magistrates to evict 
anyone living in a neighborhood reserved by law for another race 
would provoke international outrage 
chris heunis minister of constitutional development and 
planning said the measure would be reintroduced in parliament 
with amendments specifying that evictions not be mandatory 
the amended bill however would retain other provisions 
strengthening enforcement of residential segregation leaders of 
the parliaments asian and mixedrace chambers which cannot block 
most governmentbacked bills said their houses would adjourn 
indefinitely to protest the new legislation 
heunis said the amended bill would allow government officials to 
consider the availability of alternative housing and other 
humanitarian considerations before approving evictions in 
other ways he said it would remain identical to the original 
measure 
among the controversial measures remaining in the bill are those 
making it easier for authorities to confiscate property and to 
evict and prosecute people violating the group areas act the 
35yearold act designates racially segregated neighborhoods 
under both the new and old versions of the bill the maximum 
fine for property owners who allow a person to live outside his 
racial area would increase from about 165 to 4100 the maximum 
prison sentence would increase from two years to five years 
the act is a major issue in the campaign for nationwide 
municipal elections oct 26 the governments proposal to 
strengthen enforcement of the act has been seen as an accommodation 
to rightwing whites 
the government has not strictly enforced the group areas act in 
recent years angering conservative whites opposed to integrated 
neighborhoods 
president pw botha said last week he believes residential 
segregation is favored by 80 percent of whites 70 percent of 
asians and people of mixed race and a majority of blacks 
alan hendrickse leader of the mixedrace chamber of parliament 
challenged bothas claim saying his constituents favored total 
repeal of the act 
south africas black majority is excluded from parliament but 
both the mixedrace and asian chambers are expected to reject the 
group areas legislation and its amendments 
this would force the government to refer the bill to the 
presidents council a body controlled by bothas national party 
the party has the power to implement legislation over the 
opposition of the two nonwhite chambers 
parliament which reconvened monday after a midyear recess also 
is to debate legislation on creating the first open areas or 
legal multiracial neighborhoods botha would have veto power over 
any such plans 
