challenger exploded 73 seconds after launch on jan 28 1986 
killing the crew of seven 
his crewmates will be air force col richard covey the pilot 
and mission specialists george nelson mike lounge and dave 
hilmers a marine lieutenant colonel 
hauck said nasa has been hesitant to set a new date for the 
oftenpostponed launch because engineers are still troubleshooting 
two problems that developed during a test firing of discoverys 
engines on the launch pad at cape canaveral on aug 10 
one is a small leak of hydrogen gas detected in an area where 
the orbiter is joined to the external fuel tank the other is the 
apparent sluggishness of three gaseous oxygen valves in the fueling 
system 
there are some concerns about both of these he said we 
have to understand these better 
nasa officials said earlier they did not think the problems were 
serious that they were testing both systems and that they hoped to 
be able to announce resolutions and a launch date later this week 
hauck said the discovery mission is very important to the 
nation and to the space agency in getting back to flying 
lounge said he realized this is an important flight and our 
country will be looking at us but i dont feel any pressure 
because of it 
covey reported the fourday flight will be less complicated than 
most previous shuttle missions because nasa has elected to take a 
conservative approach on this first postchallenger mission 
were not breaking any new ground he said 
but covey said because of 210 modifications made to the orbiter 
the crew in essence will be making a shakedown flight of a new 
spacecraft we will have time to concentrate on those changes 
he said 
the astronauts main goal is to deploy a communications 
satellite they also will conduct 11 science and technology 
experiments 
the challenger disaster was blamed on a faulty joint in one of 
the shuttles two solid fuel booster rockets the rocket has 
undergone more than 50 modifications 
hauck said he is confident the rockets will work but the first 
two minutes of flight will be the most tense because the solids are 
converting so much kinetic energy once the solids have burned out 
and fallen away and were in smooth mainengine flight my pulse 
rate will drop he said 
hilmers said at launch time the crews thoughts will be with the 
challenger astronauts 
well be thinking of them but our thoughts will be more on 
the future than on the past he said the challenger tragedy 
was a great tragedy for the nation and a tragedy for each of us we 
cant dwell on it because if we do we might repeat the mistakes of 
the past 
hauck was asked if his crew was taking along any momentoes or 
was planning any ceremony in space for the challenger astronauts 
on the day when we have our press conference from space we 
will share them with you he replied the press conference is 
scheduled during the third day of the mission 
</TEXT>
