<TEXT>
the united states is reducing the 
number of military air operations to be flown over the persian 
gulf but has made no decision to remove warships from the area 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said monday 
when a reporter said the soviet union had urged that the united 
states withdraw its naval forces from the gulf in view of the new 
ceasefire between iran and iraq fitzwater declined comment 
but he added 
we have said in the past that as the threat diminishes in the 
gulf so would our presence we are taking some actions at this 
time to allow certain activities that have been suspended in the 
past primarily things like port calls number of sorties flown off 
the carriers a few of those kinds of things are being changed to 
reflect a more relaxed atmosphere following the ceasefire but at 
this point there has been no decision to remove ships from the 
gulf 
an administration official speaking on condition he not be 
identified said a decision was made over the weekend to fly fewer 
sorties and to make more port calls to allow sailors to rest since 
there is less need to patrol 
fitzwater said there had been no changes in the rules of 
engagement the standing operational orders given us military 
commanders 
pentagon spokesman lt col keith schneider said that since the 
ceasefire went into effect the situation in the gulf has 
stabilized and the number of operational requirements has been 
somewhat lessened 
he said sorties flown off navy aircraft carriers include both 
training exercises and missions to defend us units in the gulf 
against real or perceived threats 
the number of flights therefore fluctuates from day to day 
and as the threat to our forces in the gulf decreases the number 
of operational flights required would also diminish schneider 
said 
he also said that while the defense department has a policy 
against discussing ship schedules in advance if operational 
requirements for ships actively patrolling diminishes we will 
arrange additional port calls for rest and recreation for the 
crews 
