march by thousands of workers in the capital also is planned 
the strike is being called to protest government economic 
policies that union leaders say have caused serious inflation and 
eroded the purchasing power of workers 
most argentine unions belong to the federation its 11 previous 
general strikes have been peaceful and fairly successful shutting 
down government offices and public transportation although private 
businesses have remained open 
the cost of living rose 178 percent during the first seven 
months of this year after it increased 256 percent in july 
alfonsin devalued the austral by 114 percent against the dollar 
implemented budget cuts and instituted a system of voluntary price 
controls 
wages have not kept pace with inflation and prices continue 
rising despite voluntary controls 
the labor federation has demanded an increase in the minimum 
monthly wage from the current 66 to 121 the federation on 
friday rejected the governments offer to boost the minimum wage to 
79 
alfonsin is asking the international monetary fund for 12 
billion and the success of his economic recovery plan is a key 
issue in the may presidential and legislative elections argentina 
has a 56 billion foreign debt 
