<TEXT>
young people in the united states are living 
at home longer marrying later and taking more time to become 
selfsufficient according to a government report released monday 
assistant education secretary chester e finn jr said the study 
of youth aged 14 to 24 indicates they are staying younger 
longer 
they seem to be becoming autonomous selfsupporting 
individuals at a slower rate than was once the case finn said 
the report titled youth indicators trends in the wellbeing 
of american youth was compiled from information that had been 
collected since 1950 at federal agencies and private organizations 
finn said the figures show young people are living with their 
parents longer and they are slower to form their own families 
a number of indicators suggest that the transition from 
childhood to adulthood is taking longer and presenting more 
pitfalls than was the case several years ago the study said 
youths in the 20s are living at home measurably longer since 
1970 they have been delaying marriage to significantly later ages 
and since 1980 they have found their average earnings declining 
while those of older workers have increased 
among the findings 
the share of youth aged 18 to 24 who lived with their parents 
or in college dormitories rose from 43 percent in 1960 to 536 
percent in 1985 
the number of first marriages per 1000 nevermarried women 
aged 20 to 24 fell from 2201 in 1970 to 1044 in 1984 
median income for women aged 20 to 24 fell from 12517 in 
1980 to 12192 in 1986 using constant 1986 dollars the 
comparable figures for young men fell from 16113 in 1970 to 
14152 in 1986 
the study said the trends may be related since late marriage 
is a reasonable response to lower earnings living with parents is 
a reasonable arrangement for those not earning enough to support 
themselves 
finn said the report also showed falling scores on college 
entrance examinations and a lastplace ranking for us students in 
recent international science and mathematics tests raising concern 
about how the youth will fare in the future 
