umw and two at massey coal co subsidiaries to end selective 
strikes launched against two eastern kentucky mines in 1984 
the agreement requiring payment of 447 million to the union 
also settled a lawsuit challenging masseys decision to turn the 
leslie and mcinnes mines at sidney ky into nonunion operations 
about 700 miners including hammond worked at the two mines 
until february 1983 when all but a maintenance crew were laid off 
the remaining miners lost their jobs sept 30 1984 the day before 
the two mines were sold to sidney coal co a subsidiary of ora mae 
coal co an operation owned by massey 
after the agreement was announced roberts said the 447 
million for lost wages and benefits would be divided among some 250 
miners who had been on selective strikes with each receiving 
about 18000 
hammond said the lawsuit contends that the umw breached its duty 
of fair representation by limiting the number of members who would 
receive payments the plaintiffs also contend they have been 
excluded from union meetings thus violating the organizations 
constitution 
the lawsuit asks for a jury trial plus 500 million in 
compensatory and 500 million in punitive damages 
trumka pushed for the unions use of selective strikes and on 
oct 1 1984 massey coal co became the first target after the 
company refused to sign the unions national coal wage contract 
signing would have given masseys laidoff employees companywide 
reemployment rights 
the union finally called off the sometimes violent strike in 
december 1985 when massey agreed to settlement of an unfair labor 
practice charge but selective strikes against the two subsidiaries 
continued until may 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

