<TEXT>
 
no friction gramavision fool proof 
 
this wellintentioned set of back to the roots blues by a 
group of jazz players from varied backrounds reinforces two 
lessons good intentions alone rarely get you very far and its 
not easy to blend musical styles 
fool proof combines the talents of nine jazzmen brought together 
by gramavision records president jonathan rose who was dismayed 
that many new jazz musicians were neglecting their blues roots 
the result no friction though wellplayed throughout just 
doesnt measure up as a good blues record too often the jazz 
chops sound like an intrusion on the blues arrangements and 
several of the songs lack emotional punch a fatal flaw in blues 
territory 
there are a few bright spots theres a tough workout of the old 
al green hit love and happiness the only cover on the album 
red car composed by cornetist butch morris is a good jumping 
tune and saxophonist dwight andrews title nine blues has a 
certain eerie charm if you can be charmed by 719 of moody riffing 
under a recitation of lines such as red blues brown blues 
i dont recall blues 
ultimately no friction fails to satisfy one gets the 
feeling though that the musicians here will keep the spirit of 
the project alive as they resume their own diverse work which 
might say something good about good intentions after all 
by marc rice associated press writer 
</TEXT>
