<TEXT>
the department of housing and urban 
development said monday the demands of a homeless assistance group 
to stop the sales of foreclosed singlefamily dwellings would 
bankrupt a federal housing administration mortgage insurance fund 
the fund sustained by the collection of mortgage insurance 
premiums from homebuyers who use fha mortgage insurance has helped 
millions of firsttime low and moderateincome homebuyers since 
its creation in the 1930s hud said 
if we suspended sales the fha fund would be out of operation 
by the end of 1990 said j michael dorsey hud general counsel 
earlier this month hud called off a national sales campaign 
which the department hoped would unload 15000 foreclosed 
singlefamily properties and it canceled an auction of 158 
foreclosed washington dcarea homes last weekend 
the action was taken because of the threat of a lawsuit by the 
national housing law project which claims hud is violating a 
homelessassistance law passed last year that requires government 
agencies to consider the needs of the homeless before selling 
foreclosed properties 
dorsey said hud does not consider the foreclosed singlefamily 
dwellings it is selling to be surplus property the department 
considers the homes to be inventory he said 
additionally he said hud makes available all of its foreclosed 
singlefamily homes to homeless providers at a discount of 10 
percent below fair market value before the homes are listed for 
sale to the public 
the agency also offers homeless providers leasepurchase 
agreements for the hudowned homes at a cost as low as 1 per year 
he said the provider is responsible for maintaining the property 
and paying the property taxes during the lease period 
since 1985 the agency has transferred about 200 singlefamily 
homes to homeless providers about half by sale and half by lease 
he said 
dorsey said the department is reviewing its process of making 
singlefamily homes available to homeless providers and hud 
officials plan to meet with representatives of the berkley 
califbased national housing law project soon to discuss possible 
changes 
the national housing law project however is not satisfied the 
group which assists lawyers helping indigent clients with housing 
cases is threatening again to challenge the housing sale in court 
florence roisman a staff attorney for the project said the 
group planned to file suit in michigan on tuesday to challenge a 
scheduled sale there 
</TEXT>
