<TEXT>
a group of miners monday filed a 1 
billion federal lawsuit against the united mine workers of america 
and its leadership claiming the union prevented it from recovering 
wages lost during a 3year strike 
the lawsuit contended the union did not represent the miners 
properly and discriminated against them because they did not take 
part in selective picketing 
named in the suit filed in us district court included rich 
trumka umw president cecil roberts vice president and john 
banovick secretarytreasurer each was accused of conspiring to 
keep the 406 plaintiffs from collecting benefits to which they 
should have been entitled 
jerry hammond a spokesman for the socalled forgotten 400 
said the lawsuit stemmed from an agreement reached in may between 
the umw and the at massey coal co and its subsidiaries to end 
selective strikes launched against two eastern kentucky mines in 
1984 
the agreement requiring payment of 447 million to the union 
also settled a lawsuit challenging masseys decision to turn the 
mines into nonunion operations 
about 700 miners including hammond worked at the two mines 
until february 1983 when all but a maintenance crew were laid off 
the remaining miners workers lost their jobs sept 30 1984 the 
day before the two mines were sold to sidney coal co a subsidiary 
of ora mae coal co an operation owned by massey 
after the agreement was announced roberts said the 447 
million for lost wages and benefits would be divided among about 
250 miners who had been on selective strikes with each receiving 
about 18000 
hammond of red jacket wva said the lawsuit contends that 
the umw breached its duty of fair representation by limiting the 
number of members who would receive payments 
hammond and other plaintiffs also contend they have been 
excluded from union meetings thus violating the organizations 
constitution 
the lawsuit asks for a jury trial plus 500 million in 
compensatory and 500 million in punitive damages 
in washington union spokesman joseph corcoran said late monday 
that the unions legal department had not yet seen the lawsuit but 
corcoran said the union is very confident that that settlement 
will be upheld in any court 
trumka pushed for the unions use of selective strikes and on 
oct 1 1984 massey became the first target after the company 
refused to sign the unions national coal wage contract signing 
would have given masseys laidoff employees companywide 
reemployment rights 
the union finally called off the sometimes violent strike in 
december 1985 when massey agreed to settlement of an unfair labor 
practice charge but selective strikes against the two subsidiaries 
continued until may 
</TEXT>
