<TEXT>
venezuelan president jaime lusinchi 
leveled harsh criticism at foreign commercial banks monday 
blasting them for what he called their speculative treatment of 
latin american debtors 
either we are loyal to our peoples and we look after their 
wellbeing or we yield with those who impose conditions on us and 
violate our rights and who only feel egoism opulence and 
insatiable avarice lusinchi told conference delegates from 23 
spanish and portuguesespeaking nations of america and europe 
the speculative criteria that predominates in big financial 
centers is incompatible with the interest of all people on earth 
lusinchi said 
the president spoke during the opening ceremony of the sixth 
iberoamerican conference held to organize the planned 1992 
celebrations of the 500th anniversary of the discovery of america 
lusinchis remarks come as venezuela is seeking about 25 
billion in new loans from foreign financial institutions to help 
cover a balance of payments deficit 
commercial banks widely are expected to seek economic austerity 
measures as a condition for new lending to venezuela 
lusinchi labeled as absurd latin americas current economic 
situation in which countries from mexico to argentina are 
struggling to pay foreign debts of over 400 billion venezuela 
which has a 34 billion foreign debt is the regions 
fourthlargest debtor 
this is a threat to our most elemental rights against our 
democratic stability and against our societies that want 
wellbeing and freedom he said 
lusinchi earlier this month sent a financial mission to the 
united states and europe to seek new debt financing 
venezuelan officials claim commercial bank creditors have 
reneged on a promise included in a 1987 partial debt refinancing to 
provide venezuela with new funds and help it regain access to 
international financial markets 
but despite recent rumors that venezuela might declare a 
unilateral debt payment moratorium lusinchi and other top 
administration officials have said any suspension of payments would 
occur only if the financial mission failed and only in concert with 
commercial banks 
